00:01:02.670 --> 00:01:07.440
So you use the same
method in either case,

00:01:07.440 --> 00:01:10.260
except that, of course, in
the coherent case you're

00:01:10.260 --> 00:01:13.770
working with amplitudes,
whereas in the incoherent case

00:01:13.770 --> 00:01:15.900
you're working with intensities.

00:01:15.900 --> 00:01:19.360
But apart from that,
it's identical.

00:01:19.360 --> 00:01:24.300
So what it's saying is, if you
illuminate a thin transparency,

00:01:24.300 --> 00:01:30.390
then you get a field on the far
side of this transparency which

00:01:30.390 --> 00:01:33.310
goes into your optical system.

00:01:33.310 --> 00:01:36.010
So this is his GN.

00:01:36.010 --> 00:01:39.640
And to calculate the
image, you can either

00:01:39.640 --> 00:01:45.670
do it by convolving that
with a point spread function

00:01:45.670 --> 00:01:51.280
to get the amplitude out, or you
can do it in the Fourier domain

00:01:51.280 --> 00:01:55.480
by Fourier transforming
to get the object spectra,

00:01:55.480 --> 00:02:00.430
and then multiplying it
by a transfer function

00:02:00.430 --> 00:02:04.093
and then getting the field out.

00:02:04.093 --> 00:02:06.010
And then once you've got
the field, of course,

00:02:06.010 --> 00:02:08.590
you can calculate the
intensity from that

00:02:08.590 --> 00:02:10.930
just by doing the
modulus square.

00:02:10.930 --> 00:02:13.810
So the difference
between these two things

00:02:13.810 --> 00:02:16.900
is here we working
with aptitudes,

00:02:16.900 --> 00:02:20.290
so we have a coherent
point spread function

00:02:20.290 --> 00:02:26.470
and an amplitude
transfer function,

00:02:26.470 --> 00:02:30.070
whereas for this one,
the incoherent case,

00:02:30.070 --> 00:02:33.640
we have an intensity point
spread function, which is just

00:02:33.640 --> 00:02:36.400
the modulus square of this.

00:02:36.400 --> 00:02:40.180
And here we have an optical
transfer function, which

00:02:40.180 --> 00:02:44.570
is the autocorrelation of this.

00:02:44.570 --> 00:02:47.930
So that's really
all there is to do,

00:02:47.930 --> 00:02:54.670
all there is that you need to
know about calculating images.

