00:04:43.520 --> 00:04:46.760
So you remember, we
introduced this last time.

00:04:46.760 --> 00:04:50.150
We said that if you've
got a defocused object,

00:04:50.150 --> 00:04:54.800
then you can work
out the imaging of it

00:04:54.800 --> 00:04:59.280
by using an amplitude transfer
function just like before,

00:04:59.280 --> 00:05:01.640
but it's not just
the normal one.

00:05:01.640 --> 00:05:07.550
It's modified by the
effects of defocus.

00:05:07.550 --> 00:05:11.600
What happens is that you
have to multiply the transfer

00:05:11.600 --> 00:05:17.180
function by complex exponential,
e to the i, this thing.

00:05:17.180 --> 00:05:20.300
It therefore becomes complex.

00:05:20.300 --> 00:05:24.050
And you can divide that up
into two parts, a real part

00:05:24.050 --> 00:05:26.090
and an imaginary part.

00:05:26.090 --> 00:05:29.300
The real part will image
the real information

00:05:29.300 --> 00:05:31.190
of the objects,
which is basically

00:05:31.190 --> 00:05:33.930
the absorption of the object.

00:05:33.930 --> 00:05:37.280
And that's what this shows here,
the real part of that transfer

00:05:37.280 --> 00:05:41.210
function, which is
cosine of this thing.

00:05:41.210 --> 00:05:47.400
And so this is the cutoff
of the optical system here.

00:05:47.400 --> 00:05:47.900
Sorry.

00:05:47.900 --> 00:05:49.700
No, it isn't, is it?

00:05:49.700 --> 00:05:50.240
No, sorry.

00:05:50.240 --> 00:05:53.420
The cutoff, I guess,
is some arbitrary place

00:05:53.420 --> 00:05:55.760
I guess it's not
actually shown here.

00:05:55.760 --> 00:05:58.430
But anyway, the
fact is that as you

00:05:58.430 --> 00:06:01.340
change the amount
of defocus, this

00:06:01.340 --> 00:06:05.690
will be scaled accordingly
relative to the cutoff

00:06:05.690 --> 00:06:08.490
of the transfer function.

00:06:08.490 --> 00:06:10.700
So you can imagine if
the transfer function was

00:06:10.700 --> 00:06:14.300
right in here, it would
be almost as though it was

00:06:14.300 --> 00:06:18.350
the same as an in-focus system.

00:06:18.350 --> 00:06:25.010
And then as you make the
cutoff wider and wider

00:06:25.010 --> 00:06:28.340
relative to this cos
curve, you see you getting

00:06:28.340 --> 00:06:30.050
more and more of these wiggles.

00:06:30.050 --> 00:06:36.390
So this was a case where
it's not changing very much.

00:06:36.390 --> 00:06:37.230
So there we are.

00:06:37.230 --> 00:06:41.050
There's the region
where it's non-zero,

00:06:41.050 --> 00:06:44.380
and so it's not changing
very much in that region.

00:06:44.380 --> 00:06:48.680
And so we said that
corresponds to multifocus.

00:06:48.680 --> 00:06:55.110
And then the next
case we looked at

00:06:55.110 --> 00:06:58.890
was now when it's
got a lot of defocus.

00:06:58.890 --> 00:07:02.520
So you can see here, it
starts really wiggling.

00:07:02.520 --> 00:07:04.410
Remember-- I said
this last time--

00:07:04.410 --> 00:07:07.960
this is actually cos
of this thing squared.

00:07:07.960 --> 00:07:11.510
So that's why it doesn't look
like an ordinary cos function,

00:07:11.510 --> 00:07:13.130
because of the x squared.

00:07:13.130 --> 00:07:17.850
So it scales it in
this nonlinear way.

00:07:17.850 --> 00:07:20.610
And so here's the and it
cut off again in this case.

00:07:20.610 --> 00:07:23.280
Now, in this case
you've got some wiggles,

00:07:23.280 --> 00:07:30.660
and those wiggles are going to
lead to artifacts in the image.

00:07:30.660 --> 00:07:34.660
Firstly, because of the
fact this goes negative,

00:07:34.660 --> 00:07:37.300
you can see there's some
spatial frequencies will

00:07:37.300 --> 00:07:39.800
be imaged with the wrong sign.

00:07:39.800 --> 00:07:43.210
So it's just like if
you've got a Fourier

00:07:43.210 --> 00:07:47.020
series for, let's say, a square
wave, if you take the Fourier

00:07:47.020 --> 00:07:50.590
series for a square wave and
you change the sign of some

00:07:50.590 --> 00:07:53.920
of those components, it
doesn't look like a square wave

00:07:53.920 --> 00:07:55.510
anymore.

00:07:55.510 --> 00:07:58.610
So you get a very poor
image in that case.

00:07:58.610 --> 00:08:01.860
So this is really bad
news for the image.

00:08:01.860 --> 00:08:06.370
And the other thing that
George mentions up there

00:08:06.370 --> 00:08:07.930
is that, of course,
there's regions

00:08:07.930 --> 00:08:11.390
where the value of the transfer
function is very small.

00:08:11.390 --> 00:08:15.100
So this spatial frequency
here, for example, is not

00:08:15.100 --> 00:08:16.600
going to be imaged at all.

00:08:16.600 --> 00:08:21.260
So you'll get some
gaps in the response

00:08:21.260 --> 00:08:26.321
of the different transfer
of spatial frequencies.

00:08:29.520 --> 00:08:34.500
So the significance of
depth of focus in imaging--

00:08:34.500 --> 00:08:37.530
so here he shows a 4F system.

00:08:37.530 --> 00:08:41.700
It shows here the NA
in and the NA out.

00:08:41.700 --> 00:08:44.520
And you remember, of course,
that as you changed the NA,

00:08:44.520 --> 00:08:46.650
you also change
the magnification.

00:08:46.650 --> 00:08:49.540
You change the
lateral magnification,

00:08:49.540 --> 00:08:54.210
and you also change the
longitudinal or axial

00:08:54.210 --> 00:08:55.410
magnification.

00:08:55.410 --> 00:08:58.360
That goes as the NA squared.

00:08:58.360 --> 00:09:01.710
And so we define
these two terms.

00:09:01.710 --> 00:09:05.910
Depth of field is basically
that the defocus tolerance

00:09:05.910 --> 00:09:09.810
in the object space, so far
you can move the objects

00:09:09.810 --> 00:09:14.030
without it going too
much out of focus.

00:09:14.030 --> 00:09:21.760
And so this gives some idea
about the value of that, then.

00:09:21.760 --> 00:09:24.490
The depth that
depth of a field is

00:09:24.490 --> 00:09:28.975
given by this lambda
over 2NA squared.

00:09:31.990 --> 00:09:37.300
You get this NA squared because
the longitudinal magnification

00:09:37.300 --> 00:09:40.320
also goes as NA squared.

00:09:40.320 --> 00:09:42.980
And then on the other
side, in the image side,

00:09:42.980 --> 00:09:46.160
you have a depth of focus
rather than a depth of field.

00:09:46.160 --> 00:09:50.300
Notice in the title, he calls
it DoF, which can mean either,

00:09:50.300 --> 00:09:52.290
so Depth of Field,
Depth of Focus.

00:09:52.290 --> 00:09:57.200
You'll find that, of course,
in general terminology people

00:09:57.200 --> 00:10:00.520
often use these phrases
almost interchangeably

00:10:00.520 --> 00:10:05.250
and are not very careful
about using the right one

00:10:05.250 --> 00:10:07.070
for the right space.

00:10:07.070 --> 00:10:08.870
But this is what
it really means.

00:10:08.870 --> 00:10:12.050
Depth of field is how much
you can move the object.

00:10:12.050 --> 00:10:17.120
Depth of focus is how much
you can move the screen here

00:10:17.120 --> 00:10:19.220
without it going out of focus.

00:10:19.220 --> 00:10:27.420
And you can see that this is
expressing the depth of focus

00:10:27.420 --> 00:10:30.120
now in terms of
numerical aperture.

00:10:30.120 --> 00:10:31.830
You get the same
expression, but it's now

00:10:31.830 --> 00:10:34.540
this NA rather than that one.

00:10:34.540 --> 00:10:37.440
But of course, the
magnification also

00:10:37.440 --> 00:10:40.680
goes as NA squared as well.

00:10:40.680 --> 00:10:45.210
So the image of the bit that's
in focus, here, of the object

00:10:45.210 --> 00:10:53.220
is, of course, the same as the
depth of focus of the system.

00:10:53.220 --> 00:10:55.500
Is that all clear?

00:10:55.500 --> 00:10:56.280
Yeah?

00:10:56.280 --> 00:10:57.840
Good.

00:10:57.840 --> 00:11:00.390
OK.

00:11:00.390 --> 00:11:03.330
Even though our derivations
were carried out

00:11:03.330 --> 00:11:06.870
for spatially coherent imaging,
exactly the same arguments

00:11:06.870 --> 00:11:11.730
you can use for the
incoherent case.

00:11:11.730 --> 00:11:15.030
So the idea of a--

00:11:15.030 --> 00:11:19.470
we showed the defocused
amplitude transfer function,

00:11:19.470 --> 00:11:22.740
in the same way you can
also have a defocused OTF.

00:11:27.760 --> 00:11:31.090
So let's think of
now what happens

00:11:31.090 --> 00:11:36.490
if we've got some objects which
has got some height variations.

00:11:36.490 --> 00:11:39.820
Here he's taking the
case of a surface,

00:11:39.820 --> 00:11:42.760
and he's called this
a 2 and 1/2 D object.

00:11:42.760 --> 00:11:46.060
I think he's probably called
it that because I sometimes

00:11:46.060 --> 00:11:48.122
use that terminology.

00:11:48.122 --> 00:11:49.330
I'm not the only one, really.

00:11:49.330 --> 00:11:50.440
I didn't invent it.

00:11:50.440 --> 00:11:53.860
But people often
use this 2 and 1/2 D

00:11:53.860 --> 00:11:57.640
to represent something
which is not a 2D object.

00:11:57.640 --> 00:11:59.530
It's not flat, it's
got some depth.

00:11:59.530 --> 00:12:02.830
But it's not a true
3D object in that

00:12:02.830 --> 00:12:05.090
it's got no internal structure.

00:12:05.090 --> 00:12:07.090
It's just a surface.

00:12:07.090 --> 00:12:10.720
So anyway, in this
case, this is the object

00:12:10.720 --> 00:12:12.730
and this is its image.

00:12:12.730 --> 00:12:16.510
And you can see that if
this object is quite deep,

00:12:16.510 --> 00:12:19.420
it's going to be deeper
than that depth of field

00:12:19.420 --> 00:12:20.660
of the system.

00:12:20.660 --> 00:12:24.910
And so some parts of that
are going to be out of focus.

00:12:24.910 --> 00:12:28.600
And so this is a
region, for example,

00:12:28.600 --> 00:12:31.890
which is a long way away
from the focal plane,

00:12:31.890 --> 00:12:36.090
and therefore it's going
to be imaged out of focus.

00:12:36.090 --> 00:12:40.400
And here it corresponds
to this region here.

00:12:40.400 --> 00:12:48.390
Notice, if you look at this
image, it's inverted in x.

00:12:48.390 --> 00:12:52.770
But you see that
in the z direction,

00:12:52.770 --> 00:12:56.760
a distance which is
moved this way here

00:12:56.760 --> 00:12:58.930
is also moved this way here.

00:12:58.930 --> 00:13:02.880
So there's no inversion
in the z direction.

00:13:02.880 --> 00:13:05.760
Did I hear a question over
there or was it just someone

00:13:05.760 --> 00:13:07.790
shuffling around?

00:13:07.790 --> 00:13:08.290
No.

00:13:08.290 --> 00:13:08.790
OK.

00:13:12.110 --> 00:13:17.890
So as George points out
here, what this means then

00:13:17.890 --> 00:13:21.190
for this particular object
is the point spread function

00:13:21.190 --> 00:13:24.220
is not now spatially invariant.

00:13:24.220 --> 00:13:29.440
It's a spatially
shift variance PSF

00:13:29.440 --> 00:13:32.920
because different
parts of this surface

00:13:32.920 --> 00:13:35.440
are going to experience
a different point spread

00:13:35.440 --> 00:13:37.615
function because they might
be in or out of focus.

00:13:43.520 --> 00:13:48.380
So yeah, and the part, just
like before, the part which

00:13:48.380 --> 00:13:53.270
is in focus is given by this
depth of field, which we just

00:13:53.270 --> 00:13:53.790
had before.

00:14:01.000 --> 00:14:03.360
So you can either think
of it as a depth of field

00:14:03.360 --> 00:14:06.208
or a depth of focus,
the same expression.

00:14:08.720 --> 00:14:11.160
So this is an example of this.

00:14:11.160 --> 00:14:13.860
Let's take an object
which is a letter

00:14:13.860 --> 00:14:18.650
M. I guess he didn't use MIT
this time because he wants

00:14:18.650 --> 00:14:23.390
to use the same for each so that
you can see how each of them

00:14:23.390 --> 00:14:27.210
is affected by the different
point spread function.

00:14:27.210 --> 00:14:30.320
So this is in the focal
plane, and then this

00:14:30.320 --> 00:14:33.560
is to depth of fields
out of the focal plane.

00:14:33.560 --> 00:14:36.810
This is for depth the fields
out of the focal plane.

00:14:36.810 --> 00:14:39.260
So when you image
that you can see

00:14:39.260 --> 00:14:41.780
that it's going to become--
this one's going to be in focus.

00:14:41.780 --> 00:14:43.280
It's still a bit
blurred, of course,

00:14:43.280 --> 00:14:47.250
because of the refraction
effect in the imaging.

00:14:47.250 --> 00:14:50.900
So this is convolved with
the point spread function

00:14:50.900 --> 00:14:53.570
of the coherent optical system.

00:14:53.570 --> 00:15:00.350
And then this is for the
two defocused ones, getting

00:15:00.350 --> 00:15:01.520
more and more out of focus.

00:15:05.830 --> 00:15:08.470
So right now, once
we've got that blur,

00:15:08.470 --> 00:15:10.610
what can we do about it?

00:15:10.610 --> 00:15:14.710
And there's been
quite a lot of papers

00:15:14.710 --> 00:15:17.080
that have looked at this
question of whether you

00:15:17.080 --> 00:15:20.450
can actually undo the blur.

00:15:20.450 --> 00:15:22.670
Deblurring, they
call it, or sometimes

00:15:22.670 --> 00:15:26.020
deconvolution because if
you think of the blurring

00:15:26.020 --> 00:15:28.000
as being a
convolution, you wanted

00:15:28.000 --> 00:15:31.690
to undo that, you want
to do a deconvolution.

00:15:31.690 --> 00:15:36.730
So what we actually get
then, in the Fourier domain

00:15:36.730 --> 00:15:40.420
the spectrum of the image
is equal to the spectrum

00:15:40.420 --> 00:15:45.340
of the object multiplied
by some transfer function.

00:15:45.340 --> 00:15:46.810
And this would be
true whether it's

00:15:46.810 --> 00:15:48.840
coherent or
incoherent, in general.

00:15:48.840 --> 00:15:51.280
They'd be the same
sort of effects,

00:15:51.280 --> 00:15:53.230
but you'd have to
work with intensities

00:15:53.230 --> 00:15:55.210
rather than amplitudes.

00:15:55.210 --> 00:15:59.950
And so what we say
then is that if we--

00:15:59.950 --> 00:16:02.950
this is the blurred
thing, so we can actually

00:16:02.950 --> 00:16:07.490
blur it by just dividing
by that to get rid of it.

00:16:07.490 --> 00:16:11.110
So if we get our
image, we multiply by 1

00:16:11.110 --> 00:16:13.840
over the transfer
function, and that gives us

00:16:13.840 --> 00:16:19.750
our deblurred
version of the image.

00:16:19.750 --> 00:16:24.100
So as he calls it here, you
can call it inverse filtering,

00:16:24.100 --> 00:16:27.910
or sometimes called
deconvolution.

00:16:27.910 --> 00:16:32.040
But that is actually--

00:16:32.040 --> 00:16:34.810
probably you all thought
of, that can't work.

00:16:34.810 --> 00:16:37.040
It doesn't sound as
like it ought to work.

00:16:37.040 --> 00:16:40.300
And of course, it
doesn't work very well.

00:16:40.300 --> 00:16:44.050
We're going to show a bit
more about this in a minute.

00:16:44.050 --> 00:16:46.720
In particular, it
really goes wrong

00:16:46.720 --> 00:16:50.620
if this thing goes
to 0, obviously.

00:16:50.620 --> 00:16:54.100
So you can't know
very much about that.

00:16:54.100 --> 00:16:59.440
And then also, if
it goes to something

00:16:59.440 --> 00:17:04.130
which is even very small, you
have to amplify it by a lot.

00:17:04.130 --> 00:17:07.839
And when you amplify it, you're
going to amplify the noise.

00:17:07.839 --> 00:17:10.900
So you'll end up with
a noisy reconstruction

00:17:10.900 --> 00:17:13.270
after you've done that.

00:17:13.270 --> 00:17:15.369
So this sort of
inverse filtering

00:17:15.369 --> 00:17:19.660
invariably increases
the noise in the image.

00:17:19.660 --> 00:17:24.980
And so how can we
get around that?

00:17:24.980 --> 00:17:30.160
Well, we just get around
the 0 by making it so

00:17:30.160 --> 00:17:32.300
that there isn't a 0 anymore.

00:17:32.300 --> 00:17:34.120
So this is our new version.

00:17:34.120 --> 00:17:38.350
You can see that if mu
were 0, this would just

00:17:38.350 --> 00:17:39.890
become the same as before.

00:17:39.890 --> 00:17:44.050
This is H times H star, so
the H stars would cancel,

00:17:44.050 --> 00:17:47.030
and this is 1 over H.

00:17:47.030 --> 00:17:50.920
So if this is being
compared with that,

00:17:50.920 --> 00:17:54.250
then it becomes
the same as before.

00:17:54.250 --> 00:17:59.050
But if this becomes small,
then we're just left with this,

00:17:59.050 --> 00:18:05.830
and it avoids it blowing
up and giving infinity.

00:18:05.830 --> 00:18:08.950
So if mu is 0, it reduces
to the direct filter,

00:18:08.950 --> 00:18:12.040
and we just described that
that's not a good thing to do.

00:18:12.040 --> 00:18:15.650
So the more noise
there is there,

00:18:15.650 --> 00:18:20.920
the bigger you need to
make this to avoid getting

00:18:20.920 --> 00:18:23.350
too much noise in the image.

00:18:26.630 --> 00:18:28.640
So as the noise
increases, you would tend

00:18:28.640 --> 00:18:30.500
to increase the value of mu.

00:18:35.600 --> 00:18:42.330
Yeah, so here it's saying
that if the signal and noise

00:18:42.330 --> 00:18:46.430
both obey particular
type of statistics,

00:18:46.430 --> 00:18:52.310
then you can find what the
optimum value of mu is.

00:18:52.310 --> 00:18:56.570
And we find then
that it's equal to 1

00:18:56.570 --> 00:19:00.650
over the signal-to-noise
ratio, and this

00:19:00.650 --> 00:19:03.200
is what's called a vena filter.

00:19:03.200 --> 00:19:08.420
So this N comes down to
be the same as a vena

00:19:08.420 --> 00:19:11.950
filter, which you might have
come across, some of you,

00:19:11.950 --> 00:19:13.850
in other things.

00:19:13.850 --> 00:19:18.230
So what we are doing,
really, is you're

00:19:18.230 --> 00:19:22.490
amplifying the spatial
frequencies that

00:19:22.490 --> 00:19:27.540
have been pushed down
by the imaging process.

00:19:27.540 --> 00:19:31.220
But if there is if they
become smaller than the noise,

00:19:31.220 --> 00:19:35.460
then you don't do that anymore.

00:19:35.460 --> 00:19:39.510
So he's going to give
an example of this.

00:19:39.510 --> 00:19:44.070
So this is the convolution
using this second

00:19:44.070 --> 00:19:48.370
of regularized inverse filter.

00:19:48.370 --> 00:19:58.520
And yeah, OK, he's
saying here that he's

00:19:58.520 --> 00:20:02.210
assuming he knows that
depth before he does this.

00:20:02.210 --> 00:20:08.280
So obviously, that is something
you wouldn't always necessarily

00:20:08.280 --> 00:20:09.190
know.

00:20:09.190 --> 00:20:12.700
But he knows the
depth, therefore

00:20:12.700 --> 00:20:16.530
he can calculate what
the transfer function was

00:20:16.530 --> 00:20:17.940
on the imaging side.

00:20:17.940 --> 00:20:21.030
And therefore he knows
what filter inverse

00:20:21.030 --> 00:20:24.870
filter to apply in order to
get the best reconstruction.

00:20:24.870 --> 00:20:28.170
And you can see that it works
extremely well for this one.

00:20:28.170 --> 00:20:33.390
This one is slightly blurred,
slightly a bit more blurred.

00:20:33.390 --> 00:20:35.940
And you can see also that
the background here--

00:20:35.940 --> 00:20:37.630
or at least, I can
see on this screen,

00:20:37.630 --> 00:20:39.930
but this one doesn't
show very much--

00:20:39.930 --> 00:20:43.157
the background is becoming
not black anymore.

00:20:49.580 --> 00:20:51.470
And then this is what
happens if you've

00:20:51.470 --> 00:20:56.420
got a noisy image, if you
add noise to the original--

00:20:56.420 --> 00:20:59.780
to the image before you
do the deconvolution.

00:20:59.780 --> 00:21:02.690
Now you see that
that actually it's

00:21:02.690 --> 00:21:04.220
not working nearly so well.

00:21:04.220 --> 00:21:06.080
And this one here,
you can't really

00:21:06.080 --> 00:21:08.860
make out what there is there.

00:21:08.860 --> 00:21:14.310
So this is showing that
these methods can work,

00:21:14.310 --> 00:21:19.260
but you can see
that there are also

00:21:19.260 --> 00:21:21.240
limits to how well
they can work,

00:21:21.240 --> 00:21:26.140
and especially in the
presence of noise.

00:21:26.140 --> 00:21:29.040
Actually, I should
mention that, of course,

00:21:29.040 --> 00:21:31.870
at MIT in the Media
Lab, there's a lot

00:21:31.870 --> 00:21:35.050
of work going on in
this area of what

00:21:35.050 --> 00:21:38.380
they call computational
photography, which is all

00:21:38.380 --> 00:21:46.390
to do with changing the
properties of the camera

00:21:46.390 --> 00:21:50.560
in order to make it so that
this sort of reconstruction

00:21:50.560 --> 00:21:52.340
is more efficient.

00:21:52.340 --> 00:21:55.480
So it turns out that if
you're clever about the design

00:21:55.480 --> 00:21:57.520
of the imaging system,
you can actually

00:21:57.520 --> 00:22:01.440
make it so that this
all works a lot better.

00:22:01.440 --> 00:22:04.920
But we weren't going
to go into all that.

00:22:04.920 --> 00:22:05.680
Oh, sorry.

00:22:05.680 --> 00:22:06.640
I've got this wrong.

00:22:06.640 --> 00:22:08.050
This one was the--

00:22:08.050 --> 00:22:09.702
sorry, this was the--

00:22:09.702 --> 00:22:10.660
oh, yeah, that's right.

00:22:10.660 --> 00:22:16.360
This is the image before you've
done the inverse filtering,

00:22:16.360 --> 00:22:17.950
and this is the
image after you've

00:22:17.950 --> 00:22:19.750
done the inverse filtering.

00:22:19.750 --> 00:22:21.250
So it's actually
