00:23:38.630 --> 00:23:43.160
And so today's lecture
is, first of all,

00:23:43.160 --> 00:23:48.210
about polarization, which we've
been talking about in the lab

00:23:48.210 --> 00:23:49.070
today--

00:23:49.070 --> 00:23:51.330
or yesterday, wasn't it?

00:23:51.330 --> 00:23:54.660
So that's a bit topical.

00:23:54.660 --> 00:23:59.950
And then George wrote these.

00:23:59.950 --> 00:24:03.910
So the bit that I've
added extra is basically

00:24:03.910 --> 00:24:07.300
addressing these points
here, effects of polarization

00:24:07.300 --> 00:24:12.580
on imaging in a microscope
objective or a lens

00:24:12.580 --> 00:24:16.310
with a high numerical aperture.

00:24:16.310 --> 00:24:19.400
So we'll start off
with the polarization.

00:24:19.400 --> 00:24:23.900
I'm not sure what he said about
polarization, first of all.

00:24:23.900 --> 00:24:28.310
But basically, then,
the wave equation

00:24:28.310 --> 00:24:31.400
for an electromagnetic field
is basically a vector wave

00:24:31.400 --> 00:24:32.470
equation.

00:24:32.470 --> 00:24:37.390
It's a function of
electric field here.

00:24:37.390 --> 00:24:41.230
And we had then that
the polarization

00:24:41.230 --> 00:24:46.430
is some function of
the electric field

00:24:46.430 --> 00:24:50.600
and how the relationship
between these

00:24:50.600 --> 00:24:52.710
depends on the sort of material.

00:24:52.710 --> 00:24:55.010
And so this is giving
some different examples.

00:24:55.010 --> 00:24:59.990
The simple case is this one,
which we did look at earlier,

00:24:59.990 --> 00:25:02.690
is where the polarization
is proportional

00:25:02.690 --> 00:25:04.790
to the electric field.

00:25:04.790 --> 00:25:10.340
And you remember that you get
D by adding the P to the E.

00:25:10.340 --> 00:25:16.220
And so here, this is called
the electric susceptibility,

00:25:16.220 --> 00:25:21.920
and P equals Chi times E.
So if this is a constant,

00:25:21.920 --> 00:25:23.840
this is just a linear
relationship, which

00:25:23.840 --> 00:25:26.510
is how we described it before.

00:25:26.510 --> 00:25:30.680
But there are two ways that
that can break down in practice.

00:25:30.680 --> 00:25:36.350
And usually, actually, for
materials where it breaks down,

00:25:36.350 --> 00:25:39.800
it breaks down for both at
the same time, unfortunately.

00:25:39.800 --> 00:25:41.360
So it becomes very complicated.

00:25:41.360 --> 00:25:45.650
But here we've written it with
these two effects separately.

00:25:45.650 --> 00:25:46.580
this.

00:25:46.580 --> 00:25:51.980
Is where actually the
relationship is still linear,

00:25:51.980 --> 00:25:56.480
but P is related to e
not by a simple scalar

00:25:56.480 --> 00:25:59.610
relationship like this, but
by a tensor relationship.

00:25:59.610 --> 00:26:02.630
So the direction of P is
not in the same direction

00:26:02.630 --> 00:26:05.780
as the direction
of E. And so you've

00:26:05.780 --> 00:26:10.130
got this 3 by 3
matrix, which describes

00:26:10.130 --> 00:26:12.680
the properties of the material.

00:26:12.680 --> 00:26:15.440
And this will depend on--

00:26:15.440 --> 00:26:22.250
well, for a isotopic material,
like a crystal or something

00:26:22.250 --> 00:26:26.180
like that, it would depend
on the crystal structure.

00:26:26.180 --> 00:26:32.150
Of course, if you've got some
complicated varying objects,

00:26:32.150 --> 00:26:37.760
then it can be all sorts of
even more complicated things.

00:26:37.760 --> 00:26:41.540
So that's the first case.

00:26:41.540 --> 00:26:45.260
So this is what's going to
lead to some interesting

00:26:45.260 --> 00:26:49.070
polarization effects as
you put that electric field

00:26:49.070 --> 00:26:51.540
into a crystal, for example.

00:26:51.540 --> 00:26:53.510
And then this is
the other one which

00:26:53.510 --> 00:26:57.750
is now looking at isotopic
material, but nonlinear.

00:26:57.750 --> 00:27:00.810
So this is now no
longer a constant.

00:27:00.810 --> 00:27:02.780
And so what that
means, you can you

00:27:02.780 --> 00:27:05.550
could expand it
as a power series.

00:27:05.550 --> 00:27:10.950
And you can see that there
might be some extra terms here.

00:27:10.950 --> 00:27:13.700
This is what's called
the Kerr effect.

00:27:13.700 --> 00:27:18.590
There's effectively
a susceptibility

00:27:18.590 --> 00:27:24.220
which is dependent on the
intensity of the light which

00:27:24.220 --> 00:27:24.960
shines on it.

00:27:27.630 --> 00:27:29.850
And of course, you
might expect that there

00:27:29.850 --> 00:27:34.380
will be higher orders of
this as well, of course.

00:27:34.380 --> 00:27:35.910
These sorts of
effects, you're only

00:27:35.910 --> 00:27:43.350
going to excite these if you
have a large value of E. It's

00:27:43.350 --> 00:27:46.110
a bit like, if you imagine
how this all comes about,

00:27:46.110 --> 00:27:48.750
this comes about
because your material

00:27:48.750 --> 00:27:52.400
is made up of atoms which
are all bonded together

00:27:52.400 --> 00:27:55.200
and joined to each
other with springs.

00:27:55.200 --> 00:27:57.580
And when you apply
the electric field,

00:27:57.580 --> 00:28:02.400
it makes these atoms
vibrate against the spring.

00:28:02.400 --> 00:28:05.670
And if the vibrations
are small, then it's

00:28:05.670 --> 00:28:07.680
all going to
satisfy Hooke's law,

00:28:07.680 --> 00:28:09.430
and it's going to be linear.

00:28:09.430 --> 00:28:13.170
But if you increase
the forcing term,

00:28:13.170 --> 00:28:17.100
then the vibrations get bigger,
Hooke's law breaks down,

00:28:17.100 --> 00:28:20.190
and the vibrations
become nonlinear.

00:28:20.190 --> 00:28:26.090
That's the basic physics
of what's going on here.

00:28:26.090 --> 00:28:28.530
So this is what's
called the Kerr effect.

00:28:28.530 --> 00:28:30.510
There is actually
another effect which

00:28:30.510 --> 00:28:33.370
George hasn't mentioned here.

00:28:33.370 --> 00:28:37.350
There's another-- you see
this is actually E cubed here.

00:28:37.350 --> 00:28:39.150
But you can have an
effect where this

00:28:39.150 --> 00:28:45.240
is E squared, which is called
the-- what's it called?

00:28:45.240 --> 00:28:47.130
The Pockels effect.

00:28:47.130 --> 00:28:49.140
I was really only asking
because I'd forgotten

00:28:49.140 --> 00:28:50.760
the word for a minute.

00:28:50.760 --> 00:28:54.150
But my students here know that
I'm always forgetting names,

00:28:54.150 --> 00:29:00.920
and they usually
come back eventually.

00:29:00.920 --> 00:29:03.250
Did you see what that did?

00:29:03.250 --> 00:29:05.930
Oh, yeah, it did
this, the relationship

00:29:05.930 --> 00:29:10.235
between the susceptibility
and the refractive index.

00:29:13.190 --> 00:29:16.480
And this is saying
that the phase delay

00:29:16.480 --> 00:29:20.240
depends on the polarization.

00:29:20.240 --> 00:29:23.300
And in this one, the
index of refraction

00:29:23.300 --> 00:29:25.910
depends on the intensity.

00:29:25.910 --> 00:29:28.160
So this is nonlinear optics.

00:29:28.160 --> 00:29:32.597
And as I say, those last
two effects very often

00:29:32.597 --> 00:29:33.180
come together.

00:29:36.090 --> 00:29:40.090
So this is now talking
about polarization of light.

00:29:40.090 --> 00:29:42.210
I think that probably
George must have mentioned

00:29:42.210 --> 00:29:45.210
this to some degree earlier on.

00:29:45.210 --> 00:29:49.980
But what this is showing,
then, is a plane wave of light.

00:29:49.980 --> 00:29:54.660
It's part linearly polarized
in the x direction--

00:29:54.660 --> 00:29:55.890
sorry, the y direction.

00:29:55.890 --> 00:29:58.110
This is taken as y.

00:29:58.110 --> 00:30:01.360
So the electric field
is in the y direction,

00:30:01.360 --> 00:30:03.700
which actually means that
the magnetic field is going

00:30:03.700 --> 00:30:06.240
to be in the x direction
because they're

00:30:06.240 --> 00:30:09.270
at right angles with each
other, if you remember.

00:30:09.270 --> 00:30:15.270
And you remember that you can
think of the wave propagating

00:30:15.270 --> 00:30:16.810
in two different ways.

00:30:16.810 --> 00:30:22.080
One is to think of it other
at a certain instant of time,

00:30:22.080 --> 00:30:25.440
so what we call here
it's a snapshot,

00:30:25.440 --> 00:30:29.610
and then we plot what
happens as a function of z.

00:30:29.610 --> 00:30:34.110
So of course, we have
to do this because it's

00:30:34.110 --> 00:30:38.310
difficult to plot it against
space and time at the same time

00:30:38.310 --> 00:30:42.550
because it's difficult to
visualize what's going on.

00:30:42.550 --> 00:30:45.660
So you can see here this
electric field is always

00:30:45.660 --> 00:30:49.770
in the same plane, and
it's a maximum here.

00:30:49.770 --> 00:30:52.740
It reduces, it becomes 0.

00:30:52.740 --> 00:30:55.890
It then increases in
the negative direction,

00:30:55.890 --> 00:30:59.280
comes back to 0 again,
and so on and so on.

00:30:59.280 --> 00:31:06.170
So this is linearly polarized
light as a function of space.

00:31:06.170 --> 00:31:11.340
And then this one shows the same
thing as a function of time.

00:31:11.340 --> 00:31:15.950
So we're looking at now one
particular value of positions

00:31:15.950 --> 00:31:18.800
that equals 0, and we're
looking at how this

00:31:18.800 --> 00:31:21.410
varies as a function of time.

00:31:21.410 --> 00:31:23.120
Exactly the same
diagram, of course.

00:31:23.120 --> 00:31:28.080
You probably saw when I
flicked to the next slide,

00:31:28.080 --> 00:31:29.280
it didn't change at all.

00:31:29.280 --> 00:31:32.225
It just changed the caption.

00:31:34.780 --> 00:31:38.560
And this is what circular
polarization does.

00:31:38.560 --> 00:31:42.490
Circular polarization, you can
see what this is trying to--

00:31:42.490 --> 00:31:44.000
it looks a bit complicated here.

00:31:44.000 --> 00:31:47.950
But what it's really doing is
actually quite straightforward.

00:31:47.950 --> 00:31:49.420
It's actually rotating.

00:31:49.420 --> 00:31:54.280
This electric vector is
rotating either with distance

00:31:54.280 --> 00:31:58.090
or with time, according to
which way you do the plot.

00:31:58.090 --> 00:32:01.310
And the length of this
line stays the same.

00:32:01.310 --> 00:32:04.870
So this is what we mean
by circular polarization.

00:32:08.580 --> 00:32:11.610
And this is showing
how, actually, you

00:32:11.610 --> 00:32:14.040
can think of
circular polarization

00:32:14.040 --> 00:32:17.150
as being made up
of two components--

00:32:17.150 --> 00:32:19.440
one linearly
polarized in this side

00:32:19.440 --> 00:32:24.850
in the y direction, one linearly
polarized in the x direction.

00:32:24.850 --> 00:32:30.500
And so you can see that
there are also out of phase

00:32:30.500 --> 00:32:32.040
by 90 degrees.

00:32:32.040 --> 00:32:39.090
So you can see now that in
this distance, position,

00:32:39.090 --> 00:32:41.050
this is plotted against z again.

00:32:41.050 --> 00:32:44.880
Here this one is a
maximum, this one is 0.

00:32:44.880 --> 00:32:47.550
