And then in this plane here,
you will get the Airy disk.

00:48:40.350 --> 00:48:44.100
So the pattern I described
a couple of slides

00:48:44.100 --> 00:48:50.530
ago for the field is in 3D space
would be in this region here.

00:48:50.530 --> 00:48:54.510
So in this plane here, you
get Fraunhofer diffraction,

00:48:54.510 --> 00:48:59.430
and then in the regions around
it you get Fresnel diffraction.

00:48:59.430 --> 00:49:03.570
But you can get quite similar
results, if you remember,

00:49:03.570 --> 00:49:05.980
by using this sort of system.

00:49:05.980 --> 00:49:09.420
So this is where
the aperture stop

00:49:09.420 --> 00:49:13.200
is not actually in the front
focal plane of the lens, but it

00:49:13.200 --> 00:49:15.210
actually in the
plane of the lens.

00:49:15.210 --> 00:49:18.960
Or you could think another way
of doing this experiment would

00:49:18.960 --> 00:49:23.520
be to get a convergent beam
and place a circular aperture

00:49:23.520 --> 00:49:25.110
in that convergent beam.

00:49:25.110 --> 00:49:27.540
So the question is, what do
you get in the focal region

00:49:27.540 --> 00:49:29.190
in that case?

00:49:29.190 --> 00:49:37.950
And it turns out that if
you satisfy this condition,

00:49:37.950 --> 00:49:43.080
that a squared over lambda
z is very large, where

00:49:43.080 --> 00:49:47.040
is a is this radius here--

00:49:47.040 --> 00:49:49.590
this is called the
Fresnel number.

00:49:49.590 --> 00:49:55.000
And if that quantity
is very large,

00:49:55.000 --> 00:49:59.490
it means that what you'll
get in this focal region

00:49:59.490 --> 00:50:01.080
is very similar to this.

00:50:01.080 --> 00:50:03.900
Actually, there's a
parabolic phase term

00:50:03.900 --> 00:50:06.010
that we described when
we did the Fourier

00:50:06.010 --> 00:50:08.220
optics that makes it different.

00:50:08.220 --> 00:50:12.510
But the intensity is going to be
the same as for this case here.

00:50:12.510 --> 00:50:14.670
So these are two
cases where you can

00:50:14.670 --> 00:50:18.040
get this Debye approximation.

00:50:18.040 --> 00:50:23.280
So in this case, it's exact
for this particular geometry.

00:50:23.280 --> 00:50:26.440
In this case, it's
an approximation

00:50:26.440 --> 00:50:31.320
which is obeyed if this
Fresnel number is very large.

00:50:31.320 --> 00:50:36.540
And then, not that
long ago, people

00:50:36.540 --> 00:50:41.050
realized that this
was an approximation,

00:50:41.050 --> 00:50:43.200
an assumption that was made.

00:50:43.200 --> 00:50:49.410
And there was a very nice
paper published by Li and Wolf,

00:50:49.410 --> 00:50:50.770
so this paper here--

00:50:50.770 --> 00:50:57.780
1984, quite a long time ago now,
but not that long, but anyway,

00:50:57.780 --> 00:51:00.810
as history goes, Li and Wolf.

00:51:00.810 --> 00:51:03.420
And they showed
what would happen

00:51:03.420 --> 00:51:06.030
if this Fresnel
number was not large

00:51:06.030 --> 00:51:08.640
but was of some
intermediate value.

00:51:08.640 --> 00:51:10.065
In this case, N equals 10.

00:51:12.670 --> 00:51:17.830
So you see what happens is that
this pattern has got distorted.

00:51:17.830 --> 00:51:21.190
You can see that it's
tending to sort of fan out.

00:51:21.190 --> 00:51:25.150
And the physical
explanation of that

00:51:25.150 --> 00:51:27.850
is that, effectively,
the light is

00:51:27.850 --> 00:51:30.790
being distracted by the
aperture and spreading

00:51:30.790 --> 00:51:34.300
because of diffraction effects.

00:51:34.300 --> 00:51:37.690
And that is superimposed
on the focusing effect.

00:51:37.690 --> 00:51:40.900
So the lens is trying
to focus the light down,

00:51:40.900 --> 00:51:45.080
and the diffraction is tending
to focus the light out.

00:51:45.080 --> 00:51:50.860
And so you get a sort of balance
between these two things.

00:51:50.860 --> 00:51:57.740
So in this focal plane here,
you get the same intensity

00:51:57.740 --> 00:52:02.250
as you would if the Debye
approximation was valid.

00:52:02.250 --> 00:52:05.940
But in the region elsewhere,
it's a bit different.

00:52:05.940 --> 00:52:11.952
It's scaled according to some
sort of affine transformation,

00:52:11.952 --> 00:52:13.160
I think it probably would be.

00:52:13.160 --> 00:52:15.080
What do you think?

00:52:15.080 --> 00:52:18.320
What do you think, [INAUDIBLE]?

00:52:18.320 --> 00:52:22.700
But one very interesting
thing that happens

00:52:22.700 --> 00:52:24.380
is that it turns
out-- you can't really

00:52:24.380 --> 00:52:26.300
see it very well
from this diagram,

00:52:26.300 --> 00:52:32.360
but the maximum intensity is no
longer in the focal plane, no

00:52:32.360 --> 00:52:35.210
longer in the
geometrical focal plane.

00:52:35.210 --> 00:52:37.700
It's shifted towards
the aperture.

00:52:37.700 --> 00:52:40.670
And that is called the
focus shift effect,

00:52:40.670 --> 00:52:42.800
and there's been a
lot of papers that

00:52:42.800 --> 00:52:47.210
have been concerned with that
and calculating what happens

00:52:47.210 --> 00:52:49.760
for lots of different cases.

00:52:49.760 --> 00:52:52.740
So that's the Debye
approximation.

00:52:52.740 --> 00:52:55.370
That shows what happens
if it isn't true.

00:52:55.370 --> 00:52:57.530
But now I'm going to go back.

00:52:57.530 --> 00:52:59.750
And all the rest I'm
going to carry on now

00:52:59.750 --> 00:53:02.810
is talking about what happens
if the paraxial approximation

00:53:02.810 --> 00:53:08.960
breaks down, but the Debye
approximation is valid.

00:53:08.960 --> 00:53:13.520
The case when the Debye
approximation is not valid

00:53:13.520 --> 00:53:17.270
and it's a high numerical
aperture is very complicated,

00:53:17.270 --> 00:53:18.890
and there have been
very few papers

00:53:18.890 --> 00:53:20.900
that I've treated that case.

00:53:20.900 --> 00:53:23.390
Anyway, tight focusing of light.

00:53:23.390 --> 00:53:27.540
We get light, we put it
into a microscope objective.

00:53:27.540 --> 00:53:30.680
The light then-- a
microscope objective,

00:53:30.680 --> 00:53:35.570
a dry microscope objective
might have a numerical aperture

00:53:35.570 --> 00:53:41.060
of 0.95, which means that the
light is converging something

00:53:41.060 --> 00:53:45.080
maybe over 70 degrees relative
to the axis, so very--

00:53:45.080 --> 00:53:48.020
you can't really think of 70
degrees as being a small angle,

00:53:48.020 --> 00:53:49.460
I guess.

00:53:49.460 --> 00:53:52.810
So the normal paraxial
approximations break down.

00:53:52.810 --> 00:53:57.300
And this is some sort of areas
where we might want to do this.

00:53:57.300 --> 00:54:00.920
The one, of course, that I'm
most interested in, microscopy,

00:54:00.920 --> 00:54:06.320
but also laser micromachining,
optical data storage,

00:54:06.320 --> 00:54:11.360
optical lithography, laser
trapping and cooling, looking

00:54:11.360 --> 00:54:14.630
at the physics of
light-atom interactions,

00:54:14.630 --> 00:54:16.850
and cavity quantum
electrodynamics.

00:54:16.850 --> 00:54:19.220
So there's a lot
of basic physics

00:54:19.220 --> 00:54:25.190
that's being done nowadays that
uses these sort of principles,

00:54:25.190 --> 00:54:27.370
too.

00:54:27.370 --> 00:54:30.410
So this is how we
model the light.

00:54:30.410 --> 00:54:33.050
Again, we've got--
just like before,

00:54:33.050 --> 00:54:35.240
we think of the
aperture as being

00:54:35.240 --> 00:54:38.720
placed in the front
focal plane of the lens.

00:54:38.720 --> 00:54:40.620
Of course, the lens
is very complicated.

00:54:40.620 --> 00:54:43.070
It's got loads of
pieces of glass in.

00:54:43.070 --> 00:54:46.970
But we think of it just
as like a black box,

00:54:46.970 --> 00:54:51.440
and we describe it just
by this surface here,

00:54:51.440 --> 00:54:54.320
which is called the
equivalent refractive locus.

00:54:54.320 --> 00:54:58.100
And what that is, is
the locus of points

00:54:58.100 --> 00:55:02.980
where this ray and
this ray intersect.

00:55:02.980 --> 00:55:08.870
And actually, if you've got
a well-designed system that

00:55:08.870 --> 00:55:12.410
is satisfies what's
called the sine condition,

00:55:12.410 --> 00:55:15.088
this surface will be a sphere.

00:55:15.088 --> 00:55:17.130
But I'm not going to go
into the details of that.

00:55:17.130 --> 00:55:22.230
I'm just going to assume it's
a sphere in what comes next.

00:55:22.230 --> 00:55:25.550
So in this case,
you've effectively

00:55:25.550 --> 00:55:30.380
got lots of plane waves
incident in the focus.

00:55:30.380 --> 00:55:34.940
But unlike the paraxial
case, we really

00:55:34.940 --> 00:55:37.580
have to take into account
now the polarization

00:55:37.580 --> 00:55:41.750
of these electric fields and
add together the electric fields

00:55:41.750 --> 00:55:43.580
in the focal region.

00:55:43.580 --> 00:55:47.570
And so this is what
happens after the light's

00:55:47.570 --> 00:55:50.660
gone through the lens.

00:55:50.660 --> 00:55:54.140
It starts off as
being plane polarized.

00:55:54.140 --> 00:56:01.080
So in my diagram here the red
represents the electric field,

00:56:01.080 --> 00:56:01.760
say.

00:56:01.760 --> 00:56:04.490
So we start off with
the electric field

00:56:04.490 --> 00:56:08.210
being plane polarized in
the vertical direction.

00:56:08.210 --> 00:56:10.990
And then after it's
gone through the lens,

00:56:10.990 --> 00:56:17.510
the rays are focused on
the focal point, which is

00:56:17.510 --> 00:56:19.700
at the center of this sphere.

00:56:19.700 --> 00:56:22.280
But if you actually
calculate what

00:56:22.280 --> 00:56:26.720
happens to the electric field
vector, this is what it does.

00:56:26.720 --> 00:56:29.510
After you've focused
it, the electric field

00:56:29.510 --> 00:56:33.500
lies on the surface of the
sphere with this geometry

00:56:33.500 --> 00:56:36.170
that-- you see that
these lines all

00:56:36.170 --> 00:56:40.460
go through a point on the
far side of the sphere.

00:56:40.460 --> 00:56:45.080
And the same is true for
the magnetic field as well.

00:56:45.080 --> 00:56:48.470
If you calculate what happens,
this is what you find happens.

00:56:48.470 --> 00:56:54.980
And you can show that this is
actually exactly the same field

00:56:54.980 --> 00:56:58.220
as you would get if you
placed at the center

00:56:58.220 --> 00:57:01.670
an electric dipole
along this axis

00:57:01.670 --> 00:57:05.010
and a magnetic dipole
along the y-axis.

00:57:05.010 --> 00:57:09.280
So if you add together those
fields, you would get this.

00:57:09.280 --> 00:57:13.900
And one more thing
to say is, you

00:57:13.900 --> 00:57:19.360
can see that if you've got a
small aperture system, low NA,

00:57:19.360 --> 00:57:21.010
you're in this region here.

00:57:21.010 --> 00:57:23.500
And you can see now it's
becoming very close to being

00:57:23.500 --> 00:57:25.060
linearly polarized again.

00:57:25.060 --> 00:57:27.460
It's only when you
get to big angles

00:57:27.460 --> 00:57:32.550
that it starts becoming
a bit more complicated.

00:57:32.550 --> 00:57:37.410
So Richards and Wolf in 1959--

00:57:37.410 --> 00:57:42.110
so this is the same Emil
Wolf who wrote the book.

00:57:42.110 --> 00:57:46.160
And in their paper--

00:57:46.160 --> 00:57:48.020
I haven't got the
reference here, I'm sorry.

00:57:48.020 --> 00:57:52.722
But anyone remember what
it was published in?

00:57:52.722 --> 00:57:54.300
I've forgotten.

00:57:54.300 --> 00:57:57.140
No, it doesn't matter.

00:57:57.140 --> 00:57:59.890
Proceedings of the Physical
Society, I think, maybe.

00:57:59.890 --> 00:58:01.140
But anyway, it doesn't matter.

00:58:01.140 --> 00:58:04.710
You can easily find it on
the web if you're after it.

00:58:04.710 --> 00:58:08.792
They showed-- you found it?

00:58:08.792 --> 00:58:10.780
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:58:10.780 --> 00:58:12.800
PROFESSOR: OK, Proceedings
of the Royal Society

00:58:12.800 --> 00:58:15.290
of London in 1959.

00:58:15.290 --> 00:58:19.220
They showed that the
field in the focal region

00:58:19.220 --> 00:58:20.840
could be written in this form.

00:58:20.840 --> 00:58:23.960
So rather than just have
one diffraction integral,

00:58:23.960 --> 00:58:28.190
we now end up with
three for the three--

00:58:28.190 --> 00:58:30.590
defining these three integrals.

00:58:30.590 --> 00:58:33.650
And then these are
the electric fields

00:58:33.650 --> 00:58:37.390
in the focal region, written
in terms of these integrals--

00:58:37.390 --> 00:58:39.110
i0, i1, and i2.

00:58:39.110 --> 00:58:44.100
And these things are very
similar to the paraxial things.

00:58:44.100 --> 00:58:49.400
The normal paraxial one is a bit
similar to this, with the j0.

00:58:49.400 --> 00:58:53.300
And this is an extra
bit which comes about

00:58:53.300 --> 00:58:59.190
because of the system
satisfying the sine condition.

00:58:59.190 --> 00:59:02.150
And I'll draw it for
you, what's happening.

00:59:02.150 --> 00:59:06.650
Basically, if this is this
aplanatic sphere surface,

00:59:06.650 --> 00:59:12.860
if you put in light,
plane polarized light,

00:59:12.860 --> 00:59:16.190
into this system,
you can see, if this

00:59:16.190 --> 00:59:20.690
is uniform intensity
when it goes in,

00:59:20.690 --> 00:59:24.950
you can see that the amount of
energy that's gone into here

00:59:24.950 --> 00:59:29.100
and the amount of energy that's
going to go into this angle,

00:59:29.100 --> 00:59:32.000
which is very much bigger,
is going to be the same.

00:59:32.000 --> 00:59:33.210
So you see what I'm saying?

00:59:33.210 --> 00:59:35.620
So this amount of
energy is going

00:59:35.620 --> 00:59:39.650
to be squeezed into this angle,
whereas this amount of energy

00:59:39.650 --> 00:59:43.350
is going to be spread
out over this angle.

00:59:43.350 --> 00:59:48.560
So this produces
this factor here.

00:59:52.710 --> 00:59:56.220
And then you can
calculate what happens.

00:59:56.220 --> 01:00:00.300
So this is-- yeah,
I'm sorry about that.

01:00:00.300 --> 01:00:02.394
You see, you write things
like that not so ti

01:00:02.394 --> 01:00:03.405
can be symmetric.

01:00:03.405 --> 01:00:07.530
But of course, what I
mean is that this is not

01:00:07.530 --> 01:00:09.120
circularly symmetric.

01:00:09.120 --> 01:00:14.730
This really should be a circle
before the modern technology

01:00:14.730 --> 01:00:17.030
distorted it.

01:00:17.030 --> 01:00:21.240
And so rather than the normal
Airy disk, what you get

01:00:21.240 --> 01:00:26.370
is this elliptical
focal spot like this.

01:00:30.470 --> 01:00:33.540
And this is another calculation.

01:00:33.540 --> 01:00:35.630
These are both from a
couple of my papers.

01:00:35.630 --> 01:00:42.830
This one is a really old
paper, 1977, really old.

01:00:42.830 --> 01:00:47.270
And this one was from a
bit more recent, 1997.

01:00:47.270 --> 01:00:49.290
So this was written
with Peter Torok.

01:00:49.290 --> 01:00:53.930
And we came up here with a
new way of calculating it

01:00:53.930 --> 01:00:59.030
where, basically, we look
at the multimodal expansion

01:00:59.030 --> 01:01:03.110
of the field over the
sphere and express it

01:01:03.110 --> 01:01:06.740
as a sum of these
spherical harmonics,

01:01:06.740 --> 01:01:08.750
the modes of the sphere.

01:01:08.750 --> 01:01:13.550
And so this becomes a very
actually quite computationally

01:01:13.550 --> 01:01:15.620
efficient way of
calculating things.

01:01:15.620 --> 01:01:17.540
And this is for
two systems, then.

01:01:17.540 --> 01:01:23.790
This is for an angle of
pi by 3, so 60 degrees,

01:01:23.790 --> 01:01:26.030
and this is for 90 degrees.

01:01:26.030 --> 01:01:30.080
So this is if you're actually
the limiting case, when

01:01:30.080 --> 01:01:33.670
you're actually focusing a
whole hemisphere of light

01:01:33.670 --> 01:01:34.840
onto the focus.

01:01:34.840 --> 01:01:38.530
And you can see that the
sort of general shape

01:01:38.530 --> 01:01:41.440
stays much the same,
but it changes a bit

01:01:41.440 --> 01:01:44.923
as you change the aperture.

01:01:44.923 --> 01:01:46.840
The other thing I was
going to say a bit about

01:01:46.840 --> 01:01:49.390
is Bessel beams.

01:01:49.390 --> 01:01:52.960
I don't think George did
anything about Bessel beams

01:01:52.960 --> 01:01:56.770
in the end, but I did
see it as a title on some

01:01:56.770 --> 01:02:00.910
on the contents of
some of the lectures,

01:02:00.910 --> 01:02:02.410
as though it was
just about to come.

01:02:02.410 --> 01:02:05.140
But maybe I just missed it.

01:02:05.140 --> 01:02:07.600
But anyway, this
is a concept that

01:02:07.600 --> 01:02:13.780
is quite interesting
at the moment.

01:02:13.780 --> 01:02:17.440
Basically, there are three ways
I'm showing here of doing it.

01:02:19.970 --> 01:02:23.720
One is what happens
if you put in your--

01:02:23.720 --> 01:02:26.960
this is the aperture
stop of this lens,

01:02:26.960 --> 01:02:30.920
and we've put this central
obstruction so that it becomes

01:02:30.920 --> 01:02:32.600
just that annular region.

01:02:32.600 --> 01:02:37.050
And we make the width of this
annulus very, very narrow.

01:02:37.050 --> 01:02:40.170
Then, you remember, just
in the last lecture,

01:02:40.170 --> 01:02:43.550
we looked at what happens
for this annular lens.

01:02:43.550 --> 01:02:46.220
And we know that
what happens is,

01:02:46.220 --> 01:02:50.960
compared with the Airy disk,
the central lobe gets narrower,

01:02:50.960 --> 01:02:53.040
but the side lobes get bigger.

01:02:53.040 --> 01:02:55.670
Well, it turns out that
in the limiting cases,

01:02:55.670 --> 01:03:01.520
this becomes very narrow, you
get the Airy disk becomes,

01:03:01.520 --> 01:03:05.240
given by this very simple
expression, just j0 squared,

01:03:05.240 --> 01:03:08.310
where j0 is a Bessel function.

01:03:08.310 --> 01:03:12.130
So that's why it's
called a Bessel beam.

01:03:12.130 --> 01:03:17.390
And it has this
very nice property

01:03:17.390 --> 01:03:22.460
that actually this is it this
satisfies the wave equation.

01:03:22.460 --> 01:03:25.290
So it's like a sort
of mode of free space.

01:03:25.290 --> 01:03:30.440
So this Bessel beam propagates
with an infinite depth

01:03:30.440 --> 01:03:32.240
of focus.

01:03:32.240 --> 01:03:34.850
It just propagates
without spreading,

01:03:34.850 --> 01:03:37.960
and so that's why
these beams have become

01:03:37.960 --> 01:03:40.160
of quite a lot of interest.

01:03:40.160 --> 01:03:43.910
Actually, the concept
is really quite old.

01:03:43.910 --> 01:03:48.980
There was a device
proposed by MacLeod in 1954

01:03:48.980 --> 01:03:52.380
for producing something
rather similar,

01:03:52.380 --> 01:03:53.990
which is called the Axicon.

01:03:53.990 --> 01:03:57.960
An Axicon is like a
conical piece of glass.

01:03:57.960 --> 01:03:59.840
It's like a conical prism.

01:03:59.840 --> 01:04:03.260
And you can see, then,
that a prism refracts

01:04:03.260 --> 01:04:06.350
the light parallel, like this.

01:04:06.350 --> 01:04:09.620
And so you can see wherever
you are along this axis

01:04:09.620 --> 01:04:12.140
you can see that
what you see is light

01:04:12.140 --> 01:04:16.880
that's coming at the
same angle, and so you

01:04:16.880 --> 01:04:21.800
can see from this how you get
this increased depth of focus

01:04:21.800 --> 01:04:23.210
of this system.

01:04:23.210 --> 01:04:27.110
And another system was proposed,
again, a long time ago,

01:04:27.110 --> 01:04:31.100
by Dyson, to do this
not with a prism

01:04:31.100 --> 01:04:33.740
but with a diffractive
optical structure.

01:04:33.740 --> 01:04:35.810
So you make a sort
of grating, which

01:04:35.810 --> 01:04:40.190
is a bit like a zone plate
except the zone plate--

01:04:40.190 --> 01:04:44.900
the rings on a zone plate
go as R squared, whereas--

01:04:44.900 --> 01:04:48.410
sorry, the width of them,
the spacing goes as 1 over R

01:04:48.410 --> 01:04:54.110
squared, whereas this one,
the rings are linearly spaced.

01:04:54.110 --> 01:04:59.390
And in this case, because the
grating is linearly spaced,

01:04:59.390 --> 01:05:01.760
all these rays go
at the same angle,

01:05:01.760 --> 01:05:03.260
and you get the
same effect as this.

01:05:06.070 --> 01:05:08.720
So that's how you
make Bessel beams.

01:05:08.720 --> 01:05:13.870
So I've been interested in
them for a very long time.

01:05:13.870 --> 01:05:18.590
And this is from another paper
of mine going back to 1978,

01:05:18.590 --> 01:05:21.140
very long time ago.

01:05:21.140 --> 01:05:24.290
And this here was one of
the lines of that paper,

01:05:24.290 --> 01:05:25.160
as it says.

01:05:25.160 --> 01:05:29.690
"A wave with zero-order Bessel
function radial distribution

01:05:29.690 --> 01:05:32.770
propagates without change."

01:05:32.770 --> 01:05:36.230
And so what this
is showing is what

01:05:36.230 --> 01:05:38.780
happens if you,
instead of thinking

01:05:38.780 --> 01:05:43.490
of the paraxial theory, what
happens to this Bessel beam

01:05:43.490 --> 01:05:48.000
if it's not a paraxial
case, if you put, say,

01:05:48.000 --> 01:05:54.410
this annular mask in front
of a high numerical aperture

01:05:54.410 --> 01:05:55.910
objective lens.

01:05:55.910 --> 01:05:57.960
And this is what you get.

01:05:57.960 --> 01:05:59.690
So this is for
different angles--

01:05:59.690 --> 01:06:02.780
30, 60, 90, as before.

01:06:02.780 --> 01:06:04.130
I've even gone further here.

01:06:04.130 --> 01:06:05.880
I've gone to 120.

01:06:05.880 --> 01:06:08.660
And you might wonder what
that could possibly mean,

01:06:08.660 --> 01:06:12.260
except it means you can
see that you could do it

01:06:12.260 --> 01:06:17.840
by using a mirror, the parabolic
mirror that George spoke

01:06:17.840 --> 01:06:20.340
about spoke about earlier.

01:06:20.340 --> 01:06:26.340
So you can have light
coming in this way,

01:06:26.340 --> 01:06:29.410
say, a narrow annular
beam coming in here,

01:06:29.410 --> 01:06:32.340
so this might correspond,
say, to this case.

01:06:32.340 --> 01:06:37.920
And then the 120 case would
be when the light's coming in

01:06:37.920 --> 01:06:40.540
like this.

01:06:40.540 --> 01:06:43.780
So you can actually get
a bigger than 90 degrees

01:06:43.780 --> 01:06:47.110
by using a mirror
sort of structure.

01:06:47.110 --> 01:06:50.950
But anyway, what you
see is what happens,

01:06:50.950 --> 01:06:54.680
if the angle of the
focusing is small,

01:06:54.680 --> 01:06:57.250
then it's pretty similar
to what I showed earlier

01:06:57.250 --> 01:07:00.520
for the full lens,
full aperture.

01:07:00.520 --> 01:07:02.890
But as you make this
angle bigger and bigger,

01:07:02.890 --> 01:07:05.920
eventually very nasty
things start happening.

01:07:05.920 --> 01:07:10.480
This thing starts splitting
into two spots rather than one,

01:07:10.480 --> 01:07:12.580
and you can see that it
does more and more of that

01:07:12.580 --> 01:07:15.220
as you make it even bigger.

01:07:15.220 --> 01:07:17.620
And so this is all
assuming that we're

01:07:17.620 --> 01:07:22.600
putting plane polarized
light into the lens.

01:07:22.600 --> 01:07:26.980
So the conclusion we come so
is that putting plane polarized

01:07:26.980 --> 01:07:29.500
light into that
lens is not really

01:07:29.500 --> 01:07:32.770
a good idea, not good news.

01:07:32.770 --> 01:07:36.610
And so this is explaining
things a bit more.

01:07:36.610 --> 01:07:40.660
First of all, we look
at the black curves.

01:07:40.660 --> 01:07:45.490
So these correspond, then-- so
a normal Airy disk is this one,

01:07:45.490 --> 01:07:48.700
and this other one
here corresponds

01:07:48.700 --> 01:07:50.590
to the narrow annulus.

01:07:50.590 --> 01:07:52.690
So you can see this
is the Bessel beam.

01:07:52.690 --> 01:07:54.850
You can see it
sharpened up quite

01:07:54.850 --> 01:08:00.760
considerably but with some
rather larger side lobes.

01:08:00.760 --> 01:08:05.430
But then if you go
to the high NA case--

01:08:05.430 --> 01:08:09.390
so this is calculating it for
a numerical aperture of 1.4,

01:08:09.390 --> 01:08:12.480
so for an [INAUDIBLE]
immersion objective.

01:08:12.480 --> 01:08:16.050
And you'll find that
for the annulus now,

01:08:16.050 --> 01:08:20.470
it's actually no narrower
than for the full lens.

01:08:20.470 --> 01:08:26.580
So the polarization effects
are really basically getting

01:08:26.580 --> 01:08:31.680
rid of any advantage in
this sharpening of the spot

01:08:31.680 --> 01:08:34.720
that we get in this case.

01:08:34.720 --> 01:08:38.600
But it turns out there is a
way of getting round that,

01:08:38.600 --> 01:08:42.149
and that is to not use plane
polarized light going in.

01:08:42.149 --> 01:08:45.359
And what we use
instead is putting

01:08:45.359 --> 01:08:47.640
radially polarized light.

01:08:47.640 --> 01:08:52.050
If we put in radially
polarized light--

01:08:52.050 --> 01:08:56.670
this corresponds to
this magenta color,

01:08:56.670 --> 01:08:58.260
so as it says here, radial.

01:08:58.260 --> 01:09:03.550
I've also called it here
TM0 because it corresponds

01:09:03.550 --> 01:09:06.910
to a transverse magnetic mode.

01:09:06.910 --> 01:09:10.029
I'll show you how that
comes about in a minute.

01:09:10.029 --> 01:09:12.840
And now you can
see for that case

01:09:12.840 --> 01:09:15.330
we're back again to
getting something

01:09:15.330 --> 01:09:19.470
very close to what you would
get for the paraxial case.

01:09:19.470 --> 01:09:22.680
So there's been a
number of papers

01:09:22.680 --> 01:09:28.260
which have exploited using
radially polarized input

01:09:28.260 --> 01:09:33.330
into your lens in order to
get a smaller focal spot.

01:09:33.330 --> 01:09:35.370
So yeah, this is
how it comes about,

01:09:35.370 --> 01:09:38.010
why it's called
transverse magnetic.

01:09:38.010 --> 01:09:43.590
So this is radially
polarized light.

01:09:43.590 --> 01:09:46.420
Sorry, yeah, the red
is the electric field.

01:09:46.420 --> 01:09:48.439
So that's in the
radial direction.

01:09:48.439 --> 01:09:51.060
If we had a small
NA, it would just

01:09:51.060 --> 01:09:53.979
be still radially polarized.

01:09:53.979 --> 01:09:58.470
But you can see that if you
look on the complete sphere,

01:09:58.470 --> 01:10:05.860
it starts becoming like
lines of longitude--

01:10:05.860 --> 01:10:08.500
latitude on the sphere.

01:10:08.500 --> 01:10:13.270
And you see the magnetic
field are these lines, which

01:10:13.270 --> 01:10:15.730
are purely transverse,
so that's why

01:10:15.730 --> 01:10:18.400
we call it transverse magnetic.

01:10:18.400 --> 01:10:22.600
And the 0 corresponds to the
fact it's the lowest order

01:10:22.600 --> 01:10:24.510
mode that's like that.

01:10:24.510 --> 01:10:30.298
There is another case which
is azimuthal polarization.

01:10:30.298 --> 01:10:31.840
This is where the
electric field goes

01:10:31.840 --> 01:10:35.540
like this and the magnetic
field is like this.

01:10:35.540 --> 01:10:38.260
So this corresponds
to TE, but I'm not

01:10:38.260 --> 01:10:41.500
going to say anything more
about that because that doesn't

01:10:41.500 --> 01:10:42.715
produce anything useful.

01:10:45.630 --> 01:10:50.340
And this is-- actually, I
said there were three ways

01:10:50.340 --> 01:10:51.840
of making these Bessel beams.

01:10:51.840 --> 01:10:59.160
There's actually a fourth way,
which some people together

01:10:59.160 --> 01:11:03.720
with me at the Data Storage
Institute here in Singapore

01:11:03.720 --> 01:11:06.120
have been working
on, and this is

01:11:06.120 --> 01:11:10.710
to use a lens with some sort
of binary optic structure.

01:11:10.710 --> 01:11:12.540
And actually, this
was from a paper

01:11:12.540 --> 01:11:15.930
where we were
simulating what happens

01:11:15.930 --> 01:11:20.580
if you put radially polarized
light into this sort of system

01:11:20.580 --> 01:11:23.970
and you optimize this
binary mask in order

01:11:23.970 --> 01:11:26.250
to get close to a Bessel beam.

01:11:26.250 --> 01:11:28.260
And these are the sort
of results you get.

01:11:28.260 --> 01:11:31.050
This is along the axis you
can see that you get something

01:11:31.050 --> 01:11:34.800
which really propagates
without spreading over

01:11:34.800 --> 01:11:35.745
quite a long distance.

01:11:42.840 --> 01:11:50.250
This is showing how there are
various ways of specifying how

01:11:50.250 --> 01:11:53.280
the performance of
a focusing system.

01:11:53.280 --> 01:11:59.880
And one way is to calculate
or measure the electric field

01:11:59.880 --> 01:12:03.540
at the focal point for a given
amount of power going in.

01:12:03.540 --> 01:12:06.690
And what you want, of course,
is for the power of the focus

01:12:06.690 --> 01:12:07.860
to be--

01:12:07.860 --> 01:12:10.960
the electric field at the
focus to be as big as possible.

01:12:10.960 --> 01:12:15.430
And so this ratio is
this thing called F here.

01:12:15.430 --> 01:12:20.580
And what this is showing is
that this one here is actually

01:12:20.580 --> 01:12:24.930
for our plane polarized light
going in and showing what

01:12:24.930 --> 01:12:28.170
happens to this
ratio as you increase

01:12:28.170 --> 01:12:30.280
the aperture of the lens.

01:12:30.280 --> 01:12:32.340
And so you can see
that as you increase

01:12:32.340 --> 01:12:35.160
the aperture of the
lens, so, of course,

01:12:35.160 --> 01:12:37.470
it focuses better and better.

01:12:37.470 --> 01:12:39.330
And therefore for the
same amount of power

01:12:39.330 --> 01:12:43.110
get getting going in, you get
a higher field at the focus.

01:12:43.110 --> 01:12:45.870
So that's why it
rises like this.

01:12:45.870 --> 01:12:50.130
But it, you see, only
gets to eventually--

01:12:50.130 --> 01:12:52.920
the maximum it ever
gets to is a half.

01:12:52.920 --> 01:12:56.730
And the reason it gets
to a half is because--

01:12:56.730 --> 01:12:59.220
I showed that this
polarization is actually

01:12:59.220 --> 01:13:04.830
equivalent to an electric
dipole plus a magnetic dipole.

01:13:04.830 --> 01:13:11.830
And so only half of the power is
going into the electric dipole,

01:13:11.830 --> 01:13:14.490
and it's the electric dipole
that gives an electric field

01:13:14.490 --> 01:13:15.420
at the center.

01:13:15.420 --> 01:13:18.150
The magnetic dipole
gives a magnetic field

01:13:18.150 --> 01:13:19.930
at the center,
which we don't want.

01:13:19.930 --> 01:13:23.400
So only half of the power is
going into the right thing.

01:13:23.400 --> 01:13:25.620
So that's why that does that.

01:13:25.620 --> 01:13:29.250
And then you can see there
another two curves here.

01:13:29.250 --> 01:13:32.980
This one is our radially
polarized light.

01:13:32.980 --> 01:13:36.970
So you can see that it's very
slow to get started here,

01:13:36.970 --> 01:13:41.560
and that's because with the
radial polarized distribution,

01:13:41.560 --> 01:13:44.680
you've got very little
power near the axis anyway.

01:13:44.680 --> 01:13:48.100
So it eventually
starts taking off,

01:13:48.100 --> 01:13:51.230
and you see that
at some angle here,

01:13:51.230 --> 01:13:53.090
which is really quite big--

01:13:53.090 --> 01:13:55.690
so this is 90 degrees
down here somewhere,

01:13:55.690 --> 01:13:58.510
so this is going to be maybe
80 degrees or something

01:13:58.510 --> 01:13:59.290
like that--

01:13:59.290 --> 01:14:03.690
it overtakes the plane polarized
one and becomes better.

01:14:03.690 --> 01:14:05.660
But you can see
there's another one,

01:14:05.660 --> 01:14:10.660
another curve here,
which is for just

01:14:10.660 --> 01:14:13.810
an electric dipole
on its own, so

01:14:13.810 --> 01:14:16.060
a transverse electric dipole.

01:14:16.060 --> 01:14:19.600
So rather than try
and give this field,

01:14:19.600 --> 01:14:22.150
we just might try to
get this polarization.

01:14:22.150 --> 01:14:26.090
And if we do that, then
we see we do even better.

01:14:26.090 --> 01:14:28.810
So in this region here, you
can see this is doing better

01:14:28.810 --> 01:14:31.120
than either of these other two.

01:14:31.120 --> 01:14:35.740
So this is what we call
an electric dipole wave.

01:14:35.740 --> 01:14:38.600
And this is what this
looks like, then.

01:14:38.600 --> 01:14:40.610
This mixed dipole,
which is the electric

01:14:40.610 --> 01:14:45.050
plus a magnetic dipole, is
equal to an electric dipole

01:14:45.050 --> 01:14:47.360
plus a magnetic dipole.

01:14:47.360 --> 01:14:49.820
So this is the
electric dipole field.

01:14:49.820 --> 01:14:52.820
So what we need to
do is to make it

01:14:52.820 --> 01:14:55.070
so that after we
focus the light,

01:14:55.070 --> 01:14:57.620
the electric field
of the focused light

01:14:57.620 --> 01:15:01.160
is on the surface along these
lines, like this, basically.

01:15:01.160 --> 01:15:03.940
You see that if you look in
the region near the axis,

01:15:03.940 --> 01:15:05.750
all these behave the same.

01:15:05.750 --> 01:15:08.210
They're all we're all going
to be virtually linearly

01:15:08.210 --> 01:15:08.930
polarized.

01:15:08.930 --> 01:15:11.750
It's only when you
get so big apertures

01:15:11.750 --> 01:15:14.260
that these become different.

01:15:17.550 --> 01:15:24.275
And so this is now looking at
what happens with Bessel beams.

01:15:27.970 --> 01:15:30.890
So this the so-called
mixed dipole,

01:15:30.890 --> 01:15:33.890
which is the plain
polarization case,

01:15:33.890 --> 01:15:42.800
for 30 degrees, 60 degrees,
90 degrees 150 degrees.

01:15:42.800 --> 01:15:48.790
This is for the electric dipole
case, 30 degrees, 60 degrees.

01:15:48.790 --> 01:15:54.030
Now, you see here this is
a bit better than this one.

01:15:54.030 --> 01:15:58.200
And this one, this spot
is divided into two,

01:15:58.200 --> 01:16:00.450
but this one hasn't
divided into two.

01:16:00.450 --> 01:16:03.200
But it has got these
rather large side

01:16:03.200 --> 01:16:05.350
lobes developed here.

01:16:05.350 --> 01:16:10.350
And then if you look at this
other curve, these other ones

01:16:10.350 --> 01:16:13.020
here, this is what I call a T1.

01:16:13.020 --> 01:16:15.450
So this is another mode I
haven't mentioned before.

01:16:15.450 --> 01:16:21.240
It's another TE mode, but it's
the TE1 rather than the TE0.

01:16:21.240 --> 01:16:22.950
And you can see
this one-- actually,

01:16:22.950 --> 01:16:24.450
ti's the same in
all these diagrams.

01:16:24.450 --> 01:16:26.880
It's independent
of the angle now.

01:16:26.880 --> 01:16:29.400
So you can see, actually,
this one turns out

01:16:29.400 --> 01:16:31.260
to be slightly smaller
than this one even.

01:16:34.140 --> 01:16:37.180
And this shows what
the TE1 looks like.

01:16:37.180 --> 01:16:39.280
This is TE1.

01:16:39.280 --> 01:16:44.770
So again, the electric
field is transverse.

01:16:44.770 --> 01:16:47.710
But it's not going all
the way around like TE0.

01:16:47.710 --> 01:16:50.860
It's going this way on this
side and this way on this side.

01:16:50.860 --> 01:16:53.680
So if you could make
this polarization,

01:16:53.680 --> 01:16:58.360
this would produce that results
I've just described there.

01:16:58.360 --> 01:17:01.210
So this shows all
these different types.

01:17:01.210 --> 01:17:05.580
So what do you have to put
into the lens to get that?

01:17:05.580 --> 01:17:08.410
So this is what you have
to put into the lens.

01:17:08.410 --> 01:17:12.120
So if you put it in
plane polarized light,

01:17:12.120 --> 01:17:16.260
you get this what I call
the mixed dipole case.

01:17:16.260 --> 01:17:19.680
In order to get electric
dipole polarization out,

01:17:19.680 --> 01:17:22.290
you have to put in light
that looks like this.

01:17:22.290 --> 01:17:25.740
For the magnetic dipole,
it has to look like this.

01:17:25.740 --> 01:17:27.220
See, here it's going--

01:17:27.220 --> 01:17:30.580
it's pointing in, and
here it's pointing out.

01:17:30.580 --> 01:17:35.970
And for the TE1,
it's like azimuthal.

01:17:35.970 --> 01:17:40.380
And for the TM1, it's
radial, like this.

01:17:40.380 --> 01:17:42.630
So by altering the
polarization of the light that

01:17:42.630 --> 01:17:46.015
goes into the lens,
you can generate all

01:17:46.015 --> 01:17:47.265
these different mode patterns.

01:17:50.030 --> 01:17:52.010
And this is what it does.

01:17:52.010 --> 01:17:55.250
This is calculating the
area of the focal spot

01:17:55.250 --> 01:17:59.310
as a function of angle for
all of these different cases.

01:17:59.310 --> 01:18:02.870
So here there's a
whole range of them

01:18:02.870 --> 01:18:06.170
for a full lens, full
circular aperture.

01:18:06.170 --> 01:18:10.850
And this is for a few different
cases for the Bessel beam.

01:18:10.850 --> 01:18:13.640
And you can see what happens is
we want this area, of course,

01:18:13.640 --> 01:18:15.600
to be as small as possible.

01:18:15.600 --> 01:18:18.440
And you can see that
actually in this region

01:18:18.440 --> 01:18:21.530
here, the electric dipole
one is the smallest,

01:18:21.530 --> 01:18:23.840
and then the TE1
is the smallest,

01:18:23.840 --> 01:18:27.890
and then eventually the radial
one becomes the smallest.

01:18:27.890 --> 01:18:30.740
But this doesn't
become bigger until you

01:18:30.740 --> 01:18:35.230
get over a numerical
aperture of 0.89.

01:18:35.230 --> 01:18:38.260
And then this is for
the full circular case.

01:18:38.260 --> 01:18:40.960
I've got lots of
different cases here.

01:18:40.960 --> 01:18:44.290
This one corresponds
to a paraboloid mirror.

01:18:44.290 --> 01:18:48.070
This one corresponds
to basically

01:18:48.070 --> 01:18:54.130
a different apertization of
the light, which you can see it

01:18:54.130 --> 01:18:57.970
actually is doing better
here than the others,

01:18:57.970 --> 01:19:01.690
but eventually runs out of steam
when you get to big angles.

01:19:01.690 --> 01:19:05.770
And you can see here, the
TE case is the smallest,

01:19:05.770 --> 01:19:07.920
and then eventually
the radial case

01:19:07.920 --> 01:19:10.770
is the smallest after you get
above a numerical aperture

01:19:10.770 --> 01:19:16.158
0.91.

01:19:16.158 --> 01:19:17.950
Now, the other thing
you'll notice, though,

01:19:17.950 --> 01:19:20.470
about all those
spots I was showing

01:19:20.470 --> 01:19:22.240
is they're all not symmetrical.

01:19:22.240 --> 01:19:25.180
So what can we do to
make them symmetrical?

01:19:25.180 --> 01:19:30.220
Well, this fits in a bit with
what we were talking about

01:19:30.220 --> 01:19:34.000
before, the polarization case,
the circularly polarized.

01:19:34.000 --> 01:19:39.670
The TE and the TM0 are
already circularly symmetric,

01:19:39.670 --> 01:19:41.080
rotationally symmetric.

01:19:41.080 --> 01:19:44.350
This one corresponds to our
normal radial polarization.

01:19:44.350 --> 01:19:47.140
But these are the
ones, we know that x

01:19:47.140 --> 01:19:52.330
polarized plus iy polarized
equals circular polarized.

01:19:52.330 --> 01:19:55.150
So we can do similar
sorts of things

01:19:55.150 --> 01:20:00.880
with these TEs or the
electric dipole polarizations.

01:20:00.880 --> 01:20:05.170
We can add we can add one
of them along the x with one

01:20:05.170 --> 01:20:08.120
of them along the
y with an i there,

01:20:08.120 --> 01:20:10.630
and that actually is now
going to give something which

01:20:10.630 --> 01:20:13.090
is rotationally symmetric.

01:20:13.090 --> 01:20:15.610
And it actually, if you
think a lot more about it,

01:20:15.610 --> 01:20:20.620
it corresponds to
azimuthal polarization

01:20:20.620 --> 01:20:23.680
with a phase singularity,
with a vortex, a phase

01:20:23.680 --> 01:20:26.620
vortex superimposed on it.

01:20:26.620 --> 01:20:31.210
And this one corresponds to
some elliptical polarization

01:20:31.210 --> 01:20:33.580
with a phase singularity.

01:20:33.580 --> 01:20:34.960
So what I mean by this?

01:20:34.960 --> 01:20:40.680
This one, azimuthal polarization
with a phase singularity,

01:20:40.680 --> 01:20:50.360
what I mean by that is
at anywhere around here,

01:20:50.360 --> 01:20:54.320
it's polarized in the
azimuthal direction.

01:20:54.320 --> 01:20:57.530
But as you go round
here, the phase

01:20:57.530 --> 01:21:01.595
changes from 0 right
around to 2 pi.

01:21:04.710 --> 01:21:06.080
[INAUDIBLE]?

01:21:06.080 --> 01:21:06.630
No?

01:21:06.630 --> 01:21:07.780
OK.

01:21:07.780 --> 01:21:10.480
So it changes.

01:21:10.480 --> 01:21:13.550
As you go round here, it
changes from 0 to 2 pi.

01:21:13.550 --> 01:21:16.040
So where it gets back to
here, it matches up again.

01:21:16.040 --> 01:21:18.830
But here it's actually
changed by pi,

01:21:18.830 --> 01:21:22.250
so it's effectively in
the opposite direction.

01:21:22.250 --> 01:21:23.510
So that's what I mean by that.

01:21:23.510 --> 01:21:25.100
There's a continuous
phase variation

01:21:25.100 --> 01:21:27.070
as you go round there.

01:21:27.070 --> 01:21:31.400
And on this one,
elliptical polarization

01:21:31.400 --> 01:21:35.870
with a phase singularity, what
it means is that the light is--

01:21:35.870 --> 01:21:40.550
anywhere on here, it's
elliptically polarized,

01:21:40.550 --> 01:21:45.320
like this, say, but
at any angle it will

01:21:45.320 --> 01:21:47.600
be a similar sort of ellipse.

01:21:47.600 --> 01:21:51.320
But the phase of
this ellipse will

01:21:51.320 --> 01:21:56.690
change with a face singularity
as you go around in the circle.

01:21:56.690 --> 01:22:02.620
And so what happens
if you do that?

01:22:02.620 --> 01:22:05.370
Well, this is what you get.

01:22:05.370 --> 01:22:07.070
So this is looking
at the cross section

01:22:07.070 --> 01:22:10.070
for three different angles
for all these different types.

01:22:10.070 --> 01:22:14.660
And so this is for
Bessel beams again.

01:22:14.660 --> 01:22:16.760
They're the simplest
to calculate.

01:22:16.760 --> 01:22:20.550
So what we find is
that for small angles,

01:22:20.550 --> 01:22:23.030
the radial polarized is no good.

01:22:23.030 --> 01:22:26.510
It turns out that the reason
why radial polarization works,

01:22:26.510 --> 01:22:29.330
actually, is because--

01:22:29.330 --> 01:22:29.830
sorry.

01:22:29.830 --> 01:22:31.960
I should have said this earlier.

01:22:31.960 --> 01:22:34.600
I don't know why
I didn't, really.

01:22:34.600 --> 01:22:39.620
Why it works is because the
light that comes down here

01:22:39.620 --> 01:22:42.600
has got some polarization
in this direction here,

01:22:42.600 --> 01:22:47.050
which means it's got a component
in this longitudinal direction.

01:22:47.050 --> 01:22:51.280
So actually, the
radially polarized light

01:22:51.280 --> 01:22:55.360
put into the lens produces a
longitudinal electric field

01:22:55.360 --> 01:22:56.680
in the focal region.

01:22:56.680 --> 01:23:00.010
And that might seem very
strange to people, first of all.

01:23:00.010 --> 01:23:01.900
You can actually
generate a wave that's

01:23:01.900 --> 01:23:07.720
moving along which has got a
longitudinal electric field.

01:23:07.720 --> 01:23:11.120
But that seems to
be what is true.

01:23:11.120 --> 01:23:15.710
But the point is, of course,
if this angle is small,

01:23:15.710 --> 01:23:19.280
then this longitudinal component
is going to be very weak.

01:23:19.280 --> 01:23:22.090
And that is why this
racially polarized one here

01:23:22.090 --> 01:23:27.220
doesn't work well, because the
transverse field is dominating

01:23:27.220 --> 01:23:29.020
over the longitudinal field.

01:23:29.020 --> 01:23:31.000
But as you increase
the aperture,

01:23:31.000 --> 01:23:35.170
you see it gets
better, like that.

01:23:35.170 --> 01:23:40.380
And then I also show
here the electric dipole.

01:23:40.380 --> 01:23:43.600
All these are all the same on
this, for this small angle,

01:23:43.600 --> 01:23:48.290
but they for the larger
anguish they become different.

01:23:48.290 --> 01:23:51.240
And this is showing how--

01:23:51.240 --> 01:23:52.410
sorry.

01:23:52.410 --> 01:23:54.770
This arrow has moved
itself for some reason.

01:23:54.770 --> 01:23:57.400
I don't know why
it's moved itself,

01:23:57.400 --> 01:24:00.210
but that this was supposed to
be pointing to this blue line

01:24:00.210 --> 01:24:03.980
here and showing
how, in this case,

01:24:03.980 --> 01:24:08.030
the TE1 case is the narrowest.

01:24:08.030 --> 01:24:11.300
It's actually even narrower
than the radial in this case

01:24:11.300 --> 01:24:15.740
here, but with some
rather slightly--

01:24:15.740 --> 01:24:17.330
some bigger side lobes here.

01:24:17.330 --> 01:24:21.550
And this shows also the
electric dipole case as well.

01:24:21.550 --> 01:24:25.850
And this one's showing how the
plane polarized case is really

01:24:25.850 --> 01:24:28.730
very bad, as we showed
earlier, once you

01:24:28.730 --> 01:24:30.050
get to really big angles.

01:24:33.280 --> 01:24:39.240
And then this is
comparing them a bit more.

01:24:39.240 --> 01:24:42.290
This is actually plotting
the normalized width

01:24:42.290 --> 01:24:44.270
of that rotationally
symmetric spot

01:24:44.270 --> 01:24:47.710
that you get, again, for
all these different cases,

01:24:47.710 --> 01:24:49.430
and showing--

01:24:49.430 --> 01:24:52.310
so these are the cases
of a full aperture.

01:24:52.310 --> 01:24:55.370
These are the cases
of a Bessel beam.

01:24:55.370 --> 01:24:57.650
And you can see that,
actually, it turns out

01:24:57.650 --> 01:25:04.390
that the TE annulus is the
narrowest, the TE Bessel beam,

01:25:04.390 --> 01:25:06.650
all the time, for any angle.

01:25:06.650 --> 01:25:10.420
It's always narrower than
the radially polarized one.

01:25:10.420 --> 01:25:14.020
And for these cases here,
for the full circular case,

01:25:14.020 --> 01:25:17.890
the TE one is always
narrower than the green one

01:25:17.890 --> 01:25:20.210
until you get to
this point here,

01:25:20.210 --> 01:25:24.100
which corresponds to a numerical
aperture of 0.98, which

01:25:24.100 --> 01:25:28.880
is higher than you would ever
get to in a practical system.

01:25:28.880 --> 01:25:33.610
So what this is all
showing is that, as I say,

01:25:33.610 --> 01:25:37.240
putting plane polarized
light in is not the optimum.

01:25:37.240 --> 01:25:41.920
It turns out that very often
the optimum can be different

01:25:41.920 --> 01:25:43.990
according to the
circumstances, but it

01:25:43.990 --> 01:25:46.960
can be this electric
dipole polarization

01:25:46.960 --> 01:25:50.890
or it can be the
radially polarized input

01:25:50.890 --> 01:25:54.100
or it can be the
transverse electric.

01:25:54.100 --> 01:25:57.150
And I think I--

01:25:57.150 --> 01:26:01.490
yeah, this is showing the
strength of the side lobes

01:26:01.490 --> 01:26:06.830
and showing how the transverse
electric might be narrower,

01:26:06.830 --> 01:26:08.480
but it might have
bigger side lobes.

01:26:08.480 --> 01:26:11.540
So here the radially polarized
has smaller side lobes,

01:26:11.540 --> 01:26:14.900
weaker side lobes, than the TE.

01:26:18.810 --> 01:26:22.800
So and there's our
conclusions about this, then.

01:26:22.800 --> 01:26:25.890
So if you focus plane
polarized light,

01:26:25.890 --> 01:26:27.960
you'll get a big focal spot.

01:26:27.960 --> 01:26:32.562
So you can improve that by
using radially polarized light,

01:26:32.562 --> 01:26:34.020
and that comes
about because you've

01:26:34.020 --> 01:26:37.920
got this strong longitudinal
field on the axis.

01:26:37.920 --> 01:26:41.280
But we find that electric
dipole polarization actually

01:26:41.280 --> 01:26:45.100
gives a higher electric
energy density at the focus,

01:26:45.100 --> 01:26:47.250
as I showed earlier,
higher than you get

01:26:47.250 --> 01:26:50.340
with radial polarized light.

01:26:50.340 --> 01:26:56.100
And then I showed that the
TE1 mode polarization gives

01:26:56.100 --> 01:26:59.400
the smallest central
lobe, and it's smaller

01:26:59.400 --> 01:27:04.320
even than you get with
radially polarized light.

01:27:04.320 --> 01:27:07.830
But the TE on its
own is asymmetric,

01:27:07.830 --> 01:27:11.200
but you can make a
symmetric version of it,

01:27:11.200 --> 01:27:14.430
which is equivalent so
azimuthal polarization

01:27:14.430 --> 01:27:17.100
with a phase singularity.

01:27:17.100 --> 01:27:23.120
So that's about it for what I
was going to say about this.

01:27:23.120 --> 01:27:25.790
So this is finishing
up the course

01:27:25.790 --> 01:27:29.810
with something which is really
sort of ongoing research

01:27:29.810 --> 01:27:33.423
and something that,
I think, there's

01:27:33.423 --> 01:27:35.090
a lot of people around
the world working

01:27:35.090 --> 01:27:38.180
on these different problems
and trying to optimize

01:27:38.180 --> 01:27:43.280
these systems to get the best
possible focusing properties

01:27:43.280 --> 01:27:45.940
that you can get
with a high NA lens.

01:27:45.940 --> 01:27:50.090
And I mentioned before all the
many different applications

01:27:50.090 --> 01:27:54.240
that there's this
could be used for.

